==Short Description==

Polkadots main targets are to solve problems of interoperability between existing blockchains, to make the network scalable and to address security issues by implementing a concept they call "Shared Security".<ref name="lightpaper"/> The backbone of the Polkadot network is the so-called Relay Chain, which is responsible to coordinate consensus and to transmit transactions among chains. Bridges link existing blockchains with any consensus algorithm to the underlying Relay Chain and thereby ensure that they become interoperable.<ref name="website"/> The last layer of Polkadot are Parachains, which are blockchains that are able to participate in the Polkadot network and process transactions in a parallelized way.<ref name="lightpaper"/> The Parachains' block headers are stored in the Relay Chains' blocks thus avoiding double-spending.<ref name="whitepaper"/> There is no limit to adding new Parachains to the network and connecting existing blockchain. To ensure security in the network, Polkadot is working on a solution that leverages collective security resources to secure all Parachains at once. The implementation of Parachains in combination with the aforementioned mechanisms enables Polkadot to be scalable and secure at the same time. There will be a DOT token released in the Genesis block that is expected to be created in fall of 2019.<ref name="lightpaper"/> The tokens' purpose will be to assign governance control to holders of DOTs and to allow consensus to be found by the implementation of some kind of Proof-of-Stake (PoS) scheme. In addition, DOTs enable adding new parachains to the network.<ref name="faq">https://polkadot.network/faq, accessed on 03.09.2018.</ref><ref name="whitepaper"/>


